      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was initially skeptical of entanglement. He felt that it was too strange, too unexplainable, and that it seemed to defy the fundamental principles of space and time. The phrase captures the sense of unease and mystification that Einstein and others felt when they first encountered entanglement – it's as if the connection between entangled particles is somehow \"haunting\" or \"mysterious\" across vast distances. This unease is also reflected in the way entanglement challenges our classical notions of causality and local realism.",
